,"links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114419"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 34-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department following a motor vehicle rollover. He complains of left shoulder pain and limited movement of his left arm. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is an obvious deformity at the left shoulder. An X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely clinical finding?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Absent left radial pulse on palpation","Reduced sharp-dull differentiation over the first three digits","Weakness of flexion of the fifth digit","Numbness over the lateral aspect of the upper arm","Reduced power of wrist extension"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe X-ray confirms an anterior dislocation of the shoulder. Axillary nerve injury is a relatively common complication of such dislocations, occurring in about 10% of patients. \u003Cstrong\u003ENumbness over the lateral aspect of the upper arm\u003C/strong\u003E is the classic presentation of axillary nerve injury, often described as a \u0027regimental badge\u0027 distribution of paraesthesia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eabsent left radial pulse\u003C/strong\u003E would suggest a vascular injury, which is a rare complication of anterior shoulder dislocation, especially in young adults. While it\u0027s important to check peripheral pulses, vascular compromise is uncommon in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced sharp-dull differentiation over the first three digits\u003C/strong\u003E would indicate median nerve involvement, which is not typically associated with shoulder dislocations. The median nerve is located more distally and is unlikely to be affected by this injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWeakness of flexion of the fifth digit\u003C/strong\u003E would suggest ulnar nerve involvement. Like the median nerve, the ulnar nerve is not commonly affected in shoulder dislocations as it runs more distally in the arm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced power of wrist extension\u003C/strong\u003E would indicate radial nerve dysfunction. While the radial nerve can be injured in some shoulder injuries, it\u0027s not a frequent complication of anterior shoulder dislocations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn managing this patient, it is crucial to perform a thorough neurovascular examination before and after reduction of the dislocation. While axillary nerve injury is the most common neurological complication, other nerves and vascular structures should also be assessed. Treatment typically involves closed reduction of the dislocation, followed by immobilisation and rehabilitation. If neurological symptoms persist after reduction, further imaging and specialist consultation may be necessary.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Axillary nerve injury is a well-recognised complication of shoulder dislocation, occurring in approximately 10% of cases.","Axillary nerve injury typically presents with numbness over the lateral aspect of the upper arm in a \u0027regimental badge\u0027 distribution.","Vascular injuries are rare complications of anterior shoulder dislocations in young adults."],"references":["Cutts S, Prempeh M, Drew S. Anterior shoulder dislocation. Ann R Coll Surg Engl 2009; 91:2-7. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2752231/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96420"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1010"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21108"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21108","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21108"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","